context: In May 2013, <a0_0>Thein Sein became the first Myanmar president to visit the White House in 47 years<a0_0/>; <a1_0>the last Burmese leader to visit the White House was Ne Win in September 1966<a1_0/>. President Barack Obama praised the former general for political and economic reforms, and the cessation of tensions between Myanmar and the United States. <a2_0>Political activists objected to the visit due to concerns over human rights abuses in Myanmar<a2_0/> but Obama assured Thein Sein that Myanmar will receive US support. The two <a3_0>leaders discussed to release more political prisoners<a3_0/>, the institutionalisation of political reform and rule of law, and ending ethnic conflict in Myanmar—the two governments agreed <a4_0>to sign a bilateral trade and investment framework agreement on 21 May 2013.
